<br>
<br>
Here are links detailing some of what I've alluded to regarding public opinion:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://politics.guardian.co.uk/polls/story/0,11030,916494,00.html">politics.guardian.co.uk/p...94,00.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
<br>
It's also important to note that pursuing a war policy has deeply fractured the ruling Labour party, numerous resignations dominated the day preceding, and the day of the vote on the war.  A record voting rebellion within the Labour party very nearly forced the government to rely on votes outside its own party to carry the motion authorising force.  <br>
<br>
Details on the House of Commons vote:<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://politics.guardian.co.uk/iraq/story/0,12956,917298,00.html">politics.guardian.co.uk/i...98,00.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
The resignation of the Leader of the Commons Robin Cook has also seriously damaged the government- in political and administrative terms he was the third most powerful man in the country behind the Prime Minister and Deputy Prime Minister.  The fact he's walked away from the core of a party and a man he's served and supported for thirty plus years is a terrible blow to the government.  Moreover, the fact that he was the Foreign secretary in the last Parliamentary session and was privy to top secret intelligence reports regarding Iraq- that added a greater weight to his opposition of a war policy.  This isn't a man who was a shouter from the back benches and a rabid left-wing politican- this was a Blair-ite and a card-carrying New Labour member, a long serving politician of high standing and centrist views.  While I applaud his enormous personal courage in taking this step, I am saddened that his influence on the cabinet is absent at this time of conflict- he will be greatly missed by the party faithful.<br>
<br>
<br>
Details on his resignation and implications here:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://politics.guardian.co.uk/iraq/story/0,12956,916124,00.html">politics.guardian.co.uk/i...24,00.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
The full text of his resignation speech to the Commons here- it makes very good reading:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://politics.guardian.co.uk/iraq/comment/0,12956,916359,00.html">politics.guardian.co.uk/i...59,00.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
